<br>
Music Cue: Learning to Fly<br>
<br>
as the scene EXPLOSIVELY opens...<br>
<br>
VARIOUS SHOTS of JAKE performing all forms of dangerous or death defying stunts; Sky diving, bungee jumping, hang gliding, demolition derby driving, speed racing....etc. until the music fades out...In NONE of the scenes is JAKE actually smiling.<br>
<br>
<br>
EXTERIOR: RACE TRACK, DAY<br>
Shot is a flip on the race track; the car is in flames...JAKE climbs out unhurt.<br>
<br>
JAKE is around 6', strong wiry build. Blonde hair, almost white, reaches his shoulders, but not long enough to be considered girlish. In fact, NOTHING about JAKE is girlish. He is a man's man, face seeming to be carved in stone. Nothing about JAKE is soft. His blue eyes reflect his soul. He is cold. Almost unfeeling. He FEARS NOTHING, even the threat of death. In fact, half the reason he takes the risks he does is for the mere fact that he laughs in the face of death, challenging it...<br>
<br>
JAKE gets to his feet after STRUGGLING from the BURNING car. PAUL, in a wheel chair, is racing across the feild to him as JAKE's PIT CREW attempts to put out the burning car. JAKE waves off the MEDIC who is attempting to see if he is alright. The PIT CREW sudden;y scatter as the car blows up. JAKE takes off his helmet, not even flinching, as he reaches PAUL.<br>
<br>
PAUL is wheelchair bound, having lost both legs in a car accident on this same track. At one point he was a strong man, but the loss of his legs has left him a shell of a man, with his own mortality and helplessness apparent in his every word and action. He is not coping with his handicap well, and JAKE has become his strength. They used to race together; now PAUL just HAUNTS the race track to watch JAKE, who he is afraid for, due to JAKE's lack of respect for danger. PAUL, while LOOKING UP to JAKE, is like your typical ex-smoker, who, after being forced to quit smoking, is trying to stop all his friends from smoking.<br>
<br>
PAUL:<br>
<br>
Jesus, Jake! You're really pushing it, man! You almost bought the farm this time!<br>
<br>
<br>
JAKE:<br>
<br>
Relax Paulie. Let me buy you a drink. (Starts walking away, unperturbed)<br>
<br>
<br>
PAUL: <br>
<br>
(Trying to keep up, arms working the wheelchair frantically)<br>
But Jake! It's like you don't even give a shit...<br>
<br>
<br>
JAKE:<br>
<br>
I don't. Now watch where you are going before you tip your ass over.<br>
<br>
<br>
PAUL:<br>
<br>
(Relaxing slightly, utters a short laugh)<br>
Right. You're telling ME to be careful.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
INTERIOR: FINNIGAN'S BAR, DAY<br>
<br>
Finnigan's is the local bar for the track's race car drivers. Many come in and go out, still dressed in their jumpsuits and still stained with grease and dirt from the track. Many beautiful female track groupies are also in abundance, hanging onto the arms and every word of the drivers. Music is playing on the jukebox in the background. JAKE and PAUL are at a corner table, JAKE in the corner, and PAUL on the outside, sitting in his wheelchair. A cute WAITRESS in a skin tight shirt and a short uniform brings the two men bottled beer, and walks off, hips swaying. PAUL forlornly watches her behind as she goes, and takes a long pull from the beer.<br>
<br>
PAUL:<br>
<br>
God DAMNED! Well, it could have been worse....I could have kept the legs and lost the family jewels.<br>
<br>
<br>
JAKE:<br>
<br>
(Staring at nothing in particular in the bar) <br>
Lot of good they'll do you. You still have to CATCH 'em when you chase 'em.<br>
<br>
<br>
PAUL:<br>
<br>
(bubble burst, but still good natured)<br>
Yeah you're right. But when I do catch 'em, they love me.<br>
<br>
<br>
JAKE:<br>
<br>
Oh yeah? Why's that?<br>
<br>
<br>
PAUL:<br>
<br>
(with a huge grin)<br>
I always let them get on top.<br>
<br>
<br>
BOTH men laugh.<br>
<br>
<br>
JAKE:<br>
<br>
But seriously man, how're you handling it?<br>
<br>
<br>
PAUL:<br>
<br>
What. the legs? It sucks man, it really sucks. (PAUSE) <br>
(Looks down at his bottle for a moment)<br>
Who the fuck am I kidding? This is HELL, Jake. Suddenly I can't do a fucking thing anymore, just because I got cocky and thought I could take that turn at a speed NOBODY should have tried. Yeah, I won the race, tumbling ass over backwards at 100 miles an hour while my legs crumpled like tin foil. What the fuck was I THINKING when I started racing in the first place?? You know what's one of the things that defines a man from a woman? A man pees standing up. I can't even fucking do that...<br>
<br>
<br>
JAKE:<br>
<br>
(Softly)<br>
Easy....<br>
<br>
<br>
PAUL:<br>
<br>
(Ignoring him)<br>
And you're another one! I seriously think you're trying to kill yourself. The crap you do scares the shit out of me. It's like you don't care what happens to yourself. I just raced, Jay...you seem to be locked into some adrenaline kick that demands if it can kill you, it turns you on...<br>
<br>
<br>
JAKE:<br>
<br>
I like the rush.<br>
<br>
<br>
PAUL:<br>
<br>
The RUSH!<br>
<br>
<br>
JAKE:<br>
<br>
The rush, Paulie. You remember it. It's what got you into the cars in the first place. Hell, people don't come to see the race; they come to see the CRASH. You knew what it was like flying down the track, staring death in the face and beating him. You were racing DEATH, man, and every time you crossed the finish line, first or last, you BEAT it. That's the rush....<br>
<br>
<br>
PAUL:<br>
<br>
(mumbling)<br>
Yeah, I beat it all right. The only rush I got was to the hospital. I didn't beat death. I just found something worse.<br>
<br>
<br>
JAKE:<br>
<br>
What's that shit? You're alive, aren't you?<br>
<br>
<br>
PAUL:<br>
<br>
(PAUSE)<br>
This ain't alive man. I feel like a crab, scuttling sideways, hoping some damned fisherman doesn't step on me too hard.<br>
<br>
<br>
JAKE:<br>
<br>
You're ALIVE.<br>
<br>
<br>
PAUL:<br>
<br>
(resignedly)<br>
Yeah.<br>
<br>
<br>
JAKE:<br>
<br>
(Breaking the mood, smiling)<br>
And...you got me....<br>
<br>
<br>
PAUL:<br>
<br>
(Short laugh)<br>
Now I really DO want to die.<br>
<br>
<br>
JAKE:<br>
<br>
You got me.<br>
<br>
<br>
PAUL:<br>
<br>
(Soft) Yeah.<br>
(Almost to himself) ...But for how long?<br>
<br>
<br>
WAITRESS approaches with another two beers. She smiles seductively at JAKE.<br>
<br>
<br>
WAITRESS:<br>
<br>
Hey Jake, I heard about the race today.<br>
<br>
<br>
JAKE:<br>
<br>
(Humoring her)<br>
Oh yeah?<br>
<br>
<br>
WAITRESS:<br>
<br>
(Leaning forward, great cleavage shot)<br>
Yeah. How fast CAN your engine go before it...explodes?<br>
<br>
<br>
JAKE:<br>
<br>
(Playing her game but holding her look steady)<br>
As fast as it needs to go. My engine doesn't know any limitations. It blows when I decide the audience needs a thrill.<br>
<br>
<br>
WAITRESS: <br>
<br>
Is that a fact?<br>
<br>
<br>
JAKE:<br>
<br>
Darlin', it's etched in stone.<br>
<br>
<br>
WAITRESS laughs and walks away, tossing next line over her shoulder.<br>
<br>
<br>
WAITRESS:<br>
<br>
Well, Jake, you ever looking for a RIDE, you know where you can find me.<br>
<br>
<br>
PAUL:<br>
<br>
(Laughing, unable to control himself, mimicking the WAITRESS)<br>
...you ever lookin' for a RIDE....JESUS, Jake!....there's two legs you won't need a key to open...!<br>
<br>
<br>
JAKE:<br>
<br>
You kidding? That woman will kill you quicker than a car crash.<br>
<br>
<br>
PAUL:<br>
<br>
Yeah, but I'd die happy. (Raising his bottle) I'd die happy...<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
EXTERIOR: OUTSIDE OF FINNIGAN'S BAR, DAY<br>
<br>
JAKE is behind the wheel of his red Porsche. PAUL is in his chair in the doorway to the bar.<br>
<br>
<br>
JAKE:<br>
<br>
You sure you don't want me to give you a ride home?<br>
<br>
<br>
PAUL:<br>
<br>
Nah. We'd just have to break down the chair and all. Mikey's got his pickup truck around back. I'll just have them toss me in the back and cart me home.<br>
<br>
<br>
JAKE: <br>
<br>
Alright. I'll give you a call tomorrow.<br>
(Peals out with a screech of tires)<br>
<br>
<br>
PAUL:<br>
<br>
(Yelling after him)<br>
And BE careful!<br>
(then, to himself)<br>
Ah, why do I even bother?<br>
<br>
(He turns around to roll back into the bar. You hear him calling to the WAITRESS from inside)<br>
<br>
Hey sweetheart! Wanna go park and neck in the handicap space?<br>
